        {
            "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
            "body": "Two other syntaxes that @jakirkham proposed in https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/3923 were class-based syntaxes\r\n\r\n```\r\nfrom cython import CEnum\r\n\r\nclass Status(CEnum):\r\n    stopped: \"Py_ssize_t\" = 0\r\n    running: \"Py_ssize_t\" = 1\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nfrom cython import cclass\r\nfrom enum import Enum\r\n\r\n@cclass\r\nclass Status(Enum):\r\n    stopped: \"Py_ssize_t\" = 0\r\n    running: \"Py_ssize_t\" = 1\r\n```\r\n\r\n(I'm not keen on the annotations on either of those). What I like here is that they match the way that Python enums are usually declared (although Python enums also have a [functional API](https://docs.python.org/3/library/enum.html#functional-api))",
